1
00:00:02,225 --> 00:00:05,128
I'd like to start with just the one down there.

2
00:00:05,147 --> 00:00:32,012
namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhasah namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhasah namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhasah

3
00:00:31,992 --> 00:00:36,536
homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:39,761 --> 00:00:45,268
I thought I'd try and answer this perennial question as to why we meditate.

5
00:00:46,630 --> 00:00:47,289
Why we meditate.

6
00:00:59,505 --> 00:01:00,987
I think one of the...

7
00:01:02,131 --> 00:01:08,338
mistakes we make, is to come to the meditation with some sort of expectation, you see.

8
00:01:10,902 --> 00:01:18,992
That expectation is a projection of what we want from the meditation, whatever it might be.

9
00:01:19,012 --> 00:01:21,975
It might be some sort of psychological relief.

10
00:01:24,739 --> 00:01:29,504
We want to cure our relationships so that everybody stops hating us.

11
00:01:31,578 --> 00:01:37,433
It might be to become enlightened, have some sort of deep spiritual experience.

12
00:01:37,453 --> 00:01:46,076
But if you come with that sort of expectation, it's getting in the way of this pure intelligence that we're trying to develop.

13
00:01:49,010 --> 00:01:56,941
So the best attitude when you come to meditate is just for the purpose of developing your skills of meditation.

14
00:01:57,242 --> 00:01:57,944
That's enough.

15
00:01:58,343 --> 00:01:59,786
Developing the skills of meditation.

16
00:02:00,707 --> 00:02:06,656
And to do that, you've got to be very clear as to what the point of it is.

17
00:02:07,358 --> 00:02:11,304
The point is to establish this moment-to-moment mindfulness.

18
00:02:12,245 --> 00:02:13,987
Moment-to-moment mindfulness.

19
00:02:16,431 --> 00:02:26,347
So if we look at the history of the Buddha himself, he starts off by practicing what we now call jhāna meditations or absorption meditations.

20
00:02:27,769 --> 00:02:37,704
And the purpose of that is to develop mental states within us through the process of certain techniques such as a mantra.

21
00:02:38,064 --> 00:02:42,692
You keep repeating something beautiful in your mind, may all beings be happy.

22
00:02:42,671 --> 00:02:51,742
And it fills the heart with a certain sensation, a certain feeling, and you keep doing that until you become absorbed in it.

23
00:02:52,022 --> 00:02:53,824
It's like watching a good film, you see.

24
00:02:54,366 --> 00:02:59,352
You just watch a good film, you get lost in it, and then when the film's ended, that's the end of that.

25
00:02:59,931 --> 00:03:06,300
So it's the same with these techniques to do with absorption or developing mental states.

26
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:34,008
they're just to do with manipulating the mind so that the heart so that some environment inner environment is created and it becomes so absorbing that you lose contact with the world you see you just become that so this was great as long as he remained in it but when he came out of it the old sufferings would arise depression, anxiety and stuff like that and

27
00:03:36,081 --> 00:03:47,542
He didn't find that satisfactory, because remember that what had awoken him to the actual, to seeking, were these two major insights.

28
00:03:47,603 --> 00:03:55,676
First of all, the fact that all life seems to end with sickness, old age and death, at some point, and aging and death.

29
00:03:57,343 --> 00:04:07,820
And that he couldn't find anything in the world as a young man which was going to give him a sense of permanent contentment, any sensual pleasure, not even relationships.

30
00:04:10,164 --> 00:04:12,990
The sort of weariness grew with it.

31
00:04:13,830 --> 00:04:20,562
These two things set him out on this task of trying to discover if there was something which was more permanent.

32
00:04:22,165 --> 00:04:31,603
So in that age, the real fear of that age was continuing rebirth, continuing reincarnation, no way out of it.

33
00:04:33,271 --> 00:04:50,790
That was the sort of underlying fear of that particular age, that all you could do was just keep being reborn, being reborn, and depending on what you did, you might be reborn as a dog, or you might be reborn as a king, but you just kept this, there was no way out of it.

34
00:04:54,988 --> 00:05:03,766
So he's looking within the concept of the age to try and find something which didn't belong to any of that, whether there was such a thing.

35
00:05:04,747 --> 00:05:16,812
Already there were some inklings with other teachings that became known as the Upanishads, that there was something which didn't belong to the phenomenal world, began to be called Atta, the Self.

36
00:05:19,086 --> 00:05:25,158
And the whole concept of it being with some greater self, Brahma, you see, was also being developed at the same time.

37
00:05:26,822 --> 00:05:32,011
So he tried all that and came up with this sort of negative position that it wasn't much cop.

38
00:05:33,334 --> 00:05:36,218
So the other process was to go into self-mortification.

39
00:05:37,120 --> 00:05:40,807
And the understanding there was that the problem lay in the body.

40
00:05:41,901 --> 00:05:51,016
So if you think about it, it's the body, isn't it, which gives us most suffering.

41
00:05:51,036 --> 00:05:56,985
The body itself, with its appetites and its sicknesses and all diseases and whatnot.

42
00:05:57,004 --> 00:06:00,569
And even when you go into feelings, even when you go into emotions, they're felt in the body.

43
00:06:02,213 --> 00:06:06,879
So if you could somehow starve the body,

44
00:06:07,552 --> 00:06:15,285
Or take the body to an excess where, in a sense, you lost contact with the body so that there was no suffering there.

45
00:06:16,927 --> 00:06:19,952
So the idea was to mortify the body.

46
00:06:22,117 --> 00:06:24,160
The most common way was to starve it.

47
00:06:24,882 --> 00:06:33,718
And those of you who've done a long fast, like the 10-day fast, know that after about three days when the body feels awful, it actually feels good, it feels all right.

48
00:06:34,860 --> 00:06:38,125
And the body feels light, and it seems to be okay.

49
00:06:38,826 --> 00:06:41,372
Except, of course, the body's eating itself.

50
00:06:41,351 --> 00:06:42,935
It won't last very long.

51
00:06:44,238 --> 00:06:48,689
So he's practicing these things and he takes it as usual to the limit.

52
00:06:49,290 --> 00:06:50,434
And he's got these companions.

53
00:06:51,175 --> 00:06:54,302
And something strikes him at some point where he realizes it's a waste of time.

54
00:06:54,564 --> 00:06:55,766
He's not getting anywhere with it.

55
00:06:57,399 --> 00:07:08,620
And he's sitting by a roadside, feeling pretty glum, and a woman comes along with a bowl of rice that she's going to offer to perhaps a shrine or something.

56
00:07:09,221 --> 00:07:12,185
So she offers it to him, this bowl of rice pudding.

57
00:07:13,786 --> 00:07:19,596
And he tastes this rice pudding, he eats this rice pudding, he feels sort of good for it.

58
00:07:20,216 --> 00:07:22,600
His body is lifted and his mind is lifted, he feels good.

59
00:07:23,502 --> 00:07:31,035
It's not that you need to eat rice pudding to become enlightened, that's not absolutely necessary.

60
00:07:31,014 --> 00:07:33,697
So then he remembers this thing in childhood, you see.

61
00:07:33,718 --> 00:07:35,060
This is really kernel stuff.

62
00:07:35,100 --> 00:07:37,762
He remembers a childhood event.

63
00:07:38,584 --> 00:07:40,605
He's watching his father doing a planet ceremony.

64
00:07:41,767 --> 00:07:54,002
And it's the state of that consciousness which he remembers as being radically different from all those things that he's practiced with the absorption states.

65
00:07:54,117 --> 00:07:58,221
and from the stuff that he's been experiencing through the self-mortification.

66
00:07:58,442 --> 00:07:59,884
There's something different about it.

67
00:08:00,384 --> 00:08:07,653
And it inspires him, so much so that he thinks that this can only be the last thing.

68
00:08:07,694 --> 00:08:11,658
He can't see anything else but that particular state that he'd been in then as a child.

69
00:08:13,079 --> 00:08:16,043
So he meditates with that, with that state.

70
00:08:16,064 --> 00:08:22,572
And within about six hours, he makes his break, which is now called enlightenment.

71
00:08:24,509 --> 00:08:25,790
So now, what is this state?

72
00:08:25,850 --> 00:08:34,623
Because then the whole of his life is about teaching people how to arrive at this state, this, for want of a better word, level of consciousness.

73
00:08:36,065 --> 00:08:50,684
So now, if you go back to your childhood, or if you watch a child, you'll see that when a child, especially around pre-language, or pre-conceptual language anyway, that's like three to seven, that sort of age, even a bit beyond that,

74
00:08:51,424 --> 00:08:54,678
You'll see that when they see something, they lock on it, don't they?

75
00:08:57,149 --> 00:08:58,335
Become totally absorbed in it.

76
00:08:58,735 --> 00:09:00,101
And you see the jaw drop.

77
00:09:00,908 --> 00:09:04,251
And they're looking at it.

78
00:09:04,272 --> 00:09:10,018
And it's only after they've absorbed this object, a beetle, that they turn around and say, what is that?

79
00:09:10,818 --> 00:09:14,943
And then, when my dad says, it's a beetle, you see.

80
00:09:14,964 --> 00:09:15,524
And that's it.

81
00:09:15,544 --> 00:09:16,706
They never see a beetle again.

82
00:09:17,466 --> 00:09:22,613
From then on, what they see is what they imagine or conceive a beetle is.

83
00:09:23,313 --> 00:09:30,662
They've lost that initial interest in it, that initial pure knowing, that initial investigative intelligence.

84
00:09:33,764 --> 00:10:03,331
yeah that make sense yeah so now what is that what is that that we have as a child which then we lose through the conceptual mind right people blame it on education but it's not education at all it's a natural progress into language and then we believe that language is more real than the actual experience we're having we actually believe we actually believe that language words are things and

85
00:10:05,927 --> 00:10:09,674
If I say car, I believe that's a thing, a car.

86
00:10:11,399 --> 00:10:12,520
Don't I?

87
00:10:14,365 --> 00:10:14,745
I do.

88
00:10:15,326 --> 00:10:18,011
But actually, all it is is an idea in my head, car.

89
00:10:20,456 --> 00:10:21,318
It has no existence.

90
00:10:21,759 --> 00:10:25,606
If you said to me, describe a car, I can describe a car to you, but it won't exist.

91
00:10:27,089 --> 00:10:27,870
It'll be in my head.

92
00:10:28,510 --> 00:10:33,557
And it'll never measure up to a real car out there, because the description will be different.

93
00:10:33,577 --> 00:10:34,519
It's made up in my head.

94
00:10:35,160 --> 00:10:39,506
If you take me to a car and ask me what it is, then of course I'll label it and say that's a car.

95
00:10:39,966 --> 00:10:46,076
But because I have a picture of a car, I might never look at that car with that open-mindedness.

96
00:10:46,096 --> 00:10:49,400
It'll have to fit into my idea of what a car is.

97
00:10:50,764 --> 00:10:53,889
And that way, I don't see the car as car.

98
00:10:55,171 --> 00:11:01,759
What I see of the car is what fits into my idea of a car.

99
00:11:01,779 --> 00:11:03,442
So now we're constantly doing that.

100
00:11:04,283 --> 00:11:10,172
Whenever you look at something, you'll see that your perception is actually distorting what you're looking at.

101
00:11:10,192 --> 00:11:14,798
And it's only when you look twice do you see things there that you hadn't seen.

102
00:11:17,966 --> 00:11:24,943
So we're always looking at the world through this glass, this coloured glass of a concept.

103
00:11:25,585 --> 00:11:34,086
And then that glass, or that distorted glass we say, is then coloured, coloured by our emotional relationship to the world.

104
00:11:36,412 --> 00:11:41,539
So whenever I see something, I always split it into all those things I like and all the things I don't like.

105
00:11:41,921 --> 00:11:46,988
So I live in this world where I have everything I like and everything I don't like.

106
00:11:47,528 --> 00:11:52,216
And as soon as I do that, I have this response to it of wanting what I like, not wanting what I don't like.

107
00:11:52,576 --> 00:11:55,360
And that's what Buddhism means by living in a dual world.

108
00:11:57,524 --> 00:11:59,628
And all those things I don't like, I don't look at properly.

109
00:12:00,009 --> 00:12:02,131
And those things I do like, I gobble up.

110
00:12:04,828 --> 00:12:07,111
So I'm always playing that game in the world.

111
00:12:07,231 --> 00:12:16,241
And the game is being empowered by some deep misunderstanding or deep commitment that I can find happiness in the world if I can get it straight.

112
00:12:17,383 --> 00:12:21,707
If I get the right partner, the right job, the right house, I'll be happy.

113
00:12:23,009 --> 00:12:25,772
And so I'm constantly manipulating the world like that.

114
00:12:26,974 --> 00:12:29,096
Just watch yourself watching TV sometimes.

115
00:12:29,115 --> 00:12:29,576
You'll see.

116
00:12:29,956 --> 00:12:31,658
If you catch yourself, you're always shifting.

117
00:12:32,580 --> 00:12:34,261
As soon as the body feels slightly uncomfortable,

118
00:12:35,423 --> 00:12:41,414
We're never actually facing the world as it is.

119
00:12:41,775 --> 00:12:46,785
We're always trying to do something to sort of shift it, to move it, to make it fit in to what I want.

120
00:12:47,988 --> 00:12:50,011
Yeah?

121
00:12:50,032 --> 00:12:55,001
So here's a Buddha, and he's found this level of consciousness.

122
00:12:55,419 --> 00:12:59,085
And he discovers a new relationship with the world.

123
00:13:00,346 --> 00:13:01,928
And then he goes out and he tries to teach it.

124
00:13:02,730 --> 00:13:07,898
So what's his ploy in trying to make us correct our vision?

125
00:13:07,937 --> 00:13:09,200
Because that's where he starts from.

126
00:13:09,740 --> 00:13:12,283
He starts from a wrong understanding.

127
00:13:12,684 --> 00:13:17,091
That wrong understanding is deep within the way we're actually seeing things.

128
00:13:18,860 --> 00:13:22,826
And what he points out is that there are three distortions that we make.

129
00:13:23,408 --> 00:13:26,613
The first is that we have some idea of continuity.

130
00:13:29,096 --> 00:13:32,423
Just think, for instance, how long is a space of time?

131
00:13:32,964 --> 00:13:35,227
How long does time last, normally?

132
00:13:36,470 --> 00:13:37,191
A couple of seconds?

133
00:13:38,673 --> 00:13:41,457
If you were to think of how long a space of time lasts...

134
00:13:43,024 --> 00:13:44,027
We stretch it, don't we?

135
00:13:44,067 --> 00:13:46,429
Because of memory and the ability to conceive.

136
00:13:47,491 --> 00:13:50,697
If you stop now, how long is time?

137
00:13:50,716 --> 00:13:54,322
A couple of seconds, isn't it?

138
00:13:56,907 --> 00:13:59,049
But actually it's not that at all, is it?

139
00:13:59,070 --> 00:14:00,052
It's absolutely specific.

140
00:14:00,091 --> 00:14:03,437
It's arising and passing away all the time at vast speeds.

141
00:14:03,657 --> 00:14:05,961
Just think of the speed of your thought.

142
00:14:06,784 --> 00:14:14,072
Just think of the speed that the eye is moving at in terms of moving around, picking up photons, making up pictures in the mind.

143
00:14:14,673 --> 00:14:18,756
And then the mind has to think what it means and then put it into some sort of thought pattern.

144
00:14:19,918 --> 00:14:21,299
Then some emotion has to come up.

145
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:22,221
We don't see any of that.

146
00:14:22,321 --> 00:14:24,822
What we catch is just this block of time.

147
00:14:27,166 --> 00:14:32,010
So the idea we have of things changing is not radical at all.

148
00:14:32,030 --> 00:14:33,211
We have a continuity.

149
00:14:33,812 --> 00:14:35,374
So when I think of myself...

150
00:14:36,366 --> 00:14:40,172
I think of myself as being the same person as I was when I was born.

151
00:14:41,313 --> 00:14:53,510
If I show you a picture of myself when I was two years old, I say, look, there, that's me, that's me, that is me when I was two years old.

152
00:14:57,397 --> 00:14:57,716
Yeah?

153
00:14:58,945 --> 00:15:00,908
That picture, this is me.

154
00:15:01,227 --> 00:15:05,953
And yet we know that physically, this body is nothing like the one we were born with.

155
00:15:06,095 --> 00:15:08,898
Every seven years, all atoms are completely changed.

156
00:15:10,740 --> 00:15:12,102
But we don't recognize that at all.

157
00:15:12,503 --> 00:15:17,068
As far as I'm concerned, this is me when I was two years old.

158
00:15:19,072 --> 00:15:25,520
So we're constantly identifying with a process, thinking that the process is me.

159
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:27,163
But the process is radical.

160
00:15:28,779 --> 00:15:31,004
There's no me that changes in it.

161
00:15:31,345 --> 00:15:40,601
So, you know, next time you stand in front of a mirror, you just point at your face and say, I didn't have that face seven years ago.

162
00:15:40,621 --> 00:15:43,948
It was a completely different face that I had seven years ago.

163
00:15:43,969 --> 00:15:51,682
And if you can imagine looking in the mirror one day and you see somebody else's face, then that break of continuity would be shocking, wouldn't it?

164
00:15:53,114 --> 00:15:56,238
Because you identify with that whole process, you see.

165
00:15:56,677 --> 00:16:10,554
So what the Buddha is saying is, if in your meditation you can really come down to a present moment and see this quality of change, then you'll break through that illusion, you'll break through that delusion of thinking that anything is actually continuous.

166
00:16:14,038 --> 00:16:20,927
Now one of the benefits of seeing that is that when you really grasp the fact that everything is arising and passing away,

167
00:16:22,948 --> 00:16:27,214
What's the point of holding on to it?

168
00:16:27,234 --> 00:16:32,160
What's the point of attaching to something which doesn't actually exist, which is only a concept in the mind?

169
00:16:35,124 --> 00:16:40,431
Yeah?

170
00:16:40,471 --> 00:16:49,142
When you do that, you begin to undermine the idea that perhaps there's something here which I can grasp onto, which is going to actually make me happy.

171
00:16:54,386 --> 00:17:02,634
So you undermine that grasping nature about life where you're trying to manipulate the world in order to make you happy.

172
00:17:03,075 --> 00:17:12,462
Because all you're doing really is just shoring up trouble for ourselves.

173
00:17:12,482 --> 00:17:14,265
So these are the sorts of insights he makes.

174
00:17:14,826 --> 00:17:19,088
And the insights he makes comes from a different level of consciousness.

175
00:17:19,329 --> 00:17:22,992
It can't be that awareness which is caught up in those things.

176
00:17:24,407 --> 00:17:46,972
So when you come to meditate, all these techniques that you come across, doesn't matter what the technique is, or what school it belongs to, is to try and lift the meditator to this particular observation post, which is not caught up in this whole business of paying pleasure, wanting, not wanting, and seeing things as continuous.

177
00:17:49,045 --> 00:17:53,751
So that's why you always begin by first of all trying to concentrate the mind.

178
00:17:53,771 --> 00:17:55,294
There has to be some stillness there.

179
00:17:55,974 --> 00:18:07,711
It doesn't matter how long it takes, but you have to wait until there's at least a somewhat ability to just stay, generally speaking, in the present moment.

180
00:18:08,434 --> 00:18:09,636
And that takes an effort.

181
00:18:10,838 --> 00:18:15,325
It's not the effort of building a road, and it's not the effort of writing an essay or something.

182
00:18:16,046 --> 00:18:21,974
It's just a very calm effort of reconditioning ourselves to be present.

183
00:18:21,994 --> 00:18:34,272
So when the mind wanders, and you acknowledge that the mind's wandering, it's worrying or something, by acknowledging it, you first of all become aware of what we obsess about,

184
00:18:34,777 --> 00:18:37,961
But then, you take your attention away from it.

185
00:18:38,221 --> 00:18:40,904
By taking your attention away from it, you're disempowering it.

186
00:18:43,348 --> 00:18:46,792
By not putting your attention on something, you disempower it.

187
00:18:47,134 --> 00:18:47,354
Right?

188
00:18:47,594 --> 00:18:47,914
Why?

189
00:18:48,516 --> 00:18:52,401
Because every time you attend to something, you've intended it.

190
00:18:55,704 --> 00:18:58,568
And intention is what's actually creating the conditioning.

191
00:19:03,336 --> 00:19:03,516
Yeah?

192
00:19:03,536 --> 00:19:03,635
Yeah?

193
00:19:05,152 --> 00:19:21,054
So by doing that, by noting where the mind has wandered, and you actually recognize where it is, and you turn away from it, you turn your face away from it, you turn your eyes away from it, you turn your attention away from it, when you come back to the breath, you make the intention to stay there.

194
00:19:21,674 --> 00:19:27,864
So that's empowering this new habit of being in the present.

195
00:19:27,884 --> 00:19:31,429
Once you've got that, once you've got a steadiness of being in the present,

196
00:19:32,741 --> 00:19:36,665
You can now take a different position with everything which comes up within you.

197
00:19:37,988 --> 00:19:43,192
Instead of when depression comes up, you hear these words, I am depressed.

198
00:19:43,634 --> 00:19:45,736
Like you pick up your phone and say to your friend, I'm depressed.

199
00:19:47,037 --> 00:19:48,179
Or you tell somebody, I'm angry.

200
00:19:48,199 --> 00:19:55,767
Instead of doing that, you're distancing yourself from it so that you're saying, there, there's depression, there's anger, there's happiness, there's joy.

201
00:19:56,607 --> 00:20:01,752
That little gap, that distance, makes all the world a difference.

202
00:20:03,049 --> 00:20:10,919
It takes you out of an identity with your emotions and your thoughts and your body to a position which disidentifies with it.

203
00:20:12,701 --> 00:20:14,702
So what is it that's disidentifying?

204
00:20:14,983 --> 00:20:23,093
What is it that's finding this new position where it's no longer experiencing itself as an emotion?

205
00:20:23,472 --> 00:20:25,976
No longer experiencing itself as a thought?

206
00:20:26,876 --> 00:20:29,279
No longer experiencing itself as the body?

207
00:20:30,922 --> 00:20:31,942
See, what is that?

208
00:20:32,917 --> 00:20:59,719
and the more you practice that the more you find that that's a much better resting place than to be stuck inside these emotions hijacked by these emotions confused by thoughts and that position is for want of a better word an observation post that you've found

209
00:21:01,015 --> 00:21:11,325
And it's from that post that you can begin to objectively observe what's happening inside you and begin to see these, specifically these two characteristics.

210
00:21:11,345 --> 00:21:20,273
Nothing that we experience inside us, never mind outside us, lasts for more than a second, lasts for more than a nanosecond.

211
00:21:22,154 --> 00:21:29,082
And there's nothing inside us which, if we attach to, or if we say it's me, is not going to cause us problems.

212
00:21:29,450 --> 00:21:36,818
So that ability to stay separate from it is actually creating a very different relationship with life.

213
00:21:40,163 --> 00:21:48,272
So that you become in it, you're still in your body, you're still in your thoughts, you're still in your emotions, but you're no longer confused by them.

214
00:21:50,536 --> 00:21:52,317
You're no longer dragged by them.

215
00:21:54,037 --> 00:21:56,760
So that's the purpose that we're meditating.

216
00:21:56,881 --> 00:22:06,673
We're meditating in order to establish a different level of consciousness.

217
00:22:06,692 --> 00:22:12,621
And it comes about by making that effort to be present, to be mindful in this present moment.

218
00:22:12,641 --> 00:22:14,143
And from that everything flows.

219
00:22:14,483 --> 00:22:15,565
Everything flows from that.

220
00:22:22,453 --> 00:22:23,214
Is that perfectly clear?

221
00:22:23,234 --> 00:22:23,335
Yeah.

222
00:22:26,538 --> 00:22:27,499
Not vigorously.

223
00:22:28,440 --> 00:22:29,181
Not vigorously.

224
00:22:43,439 --> 00:22:52,590
It's clear now, but in a few hours time it might be so clear again.

225
00:22:52,611 --> 00:22:53,131
I'll go here.

226
00:22:53,832 --> 00:22:54,553
Thank you.

227
00:22:57,384 --> 00:23:01,349
Well, that's the discovery, you see.

228
00:23:01,390 --> 00:23:03,291
That's the discovery.

229
00:23:04,773 --> 00:23:06,296
You can only know that by doing it.

230
00:23:07,757 --> 00:23:12,323
It's quality, it's active quality, is intuitive intelligence.

231
00:23:13,644 --> 00:23:16,367
It's an intelligence which is prior to thought.

232
00:23:18,109 --> 00:23:19,030
It's before thought.

233
00:23:19,530 --> 00:23:20,752
It doesn't work with thought.

234
00:23:21,534 --> 00:23:22,795
And it's prior to emotion.

235
00:23:23,115 --> 00:23:24,237
It's not emotional.

236
00:23:26,545 --> 00:23:27,686
And it's definitely not physical.

237
00:23:28,228 --> 00:23:30,353
So everything you look at can't be it.

238
00:23:32,698 --> 00:23:33,519
You've objectified.

239
00:23:33,538 --> 00:23:35,242
If it's an object, it can't be the subject.

240
00:23:38,229 --> 00:23:39,050
Can I make a point?

241
00:23:39,230 --> 00:23:39,771
Yeah.

242
00:23:40,534 --> 00:23:43,660
If you interact with something, if you're making something,

243
00:23:53,461 --> 00:24:02,555
No, I agree with you.

244
00:24:03,096 --> 00:24:06,201
Remember that the question was, what are you trying to do in meditation?

245
00:24:06,340 --> 00:24:07,943
This is the first position, you see.

246
00:24:08,003 --> 00:24:18,319
You're trying to isolate an experience, a quality within, which eventually turns out to be not phenomenal.

247
00:24:18,700 --> 00:24:20,363
It doesn't arise and pass away.

248
00:24:24,528 --> 00:24:31,859
And when you get into that state, even though you might be surrounded by unpleasant feelings, you just pop a question in your mind.

249
00:24:31,961 --> 00:24:32,721
Am I suffering?

250
00:24:32,801 --> 00:24:33,903
Is there suffering here?

251
00:24:38,151 --> 00:24:42,478
Well, first of all, you have to develop that state of being able to observe, you see.

252
00:24:42,878 --> 00:24:46,484
To observe an emotion as an object, not to get caught up in it.

253
00:24:54,193 --> 00:25:08,516
The example I give is, you know if you watch TV and you've got a light on, and you can see yourself watching TV.

254
00:25:10,238 --> 00:25:11,079
So now you have a choice.

255
00:25:11,099 --> 00:25:14,203
Do you watch yourself watching TV, or are you going to watch TV?

256
00:25:17,269 --> 00:25:20,673
So this intelligence senses...

257
00:25:21,750 --> 00:25:25,476
It's presence within the mind, which is like a TV screen.

258
00:25:26,698 --> 00:25:28,901
And that's where you get this feeling of an observer.

259
00:25:28,921 --> 00:25:35,609
And when you have that feeling of an observer watching what's happening, that's exactly what's happening.

260
00:25:35,630 --> 00:25:38,773
There are two consciousnesses there, one after the other, very quick.

261
00:25:39,955 --> 00:25:40,476
Very quick.

262
00:25:40,997 --> 00:25:45,462
You can't actually see it unless you've got extremely good concentration.

263
00:25:45,442 --> 00:25:53,194
where there's this sense of presence, the observer, and what it's observing.

264
00:25:53,997 --> 00:25:59,404
By continuing to put your attention on what you're observing, the observer will disappear.

265
00:26:00,125 --> 00:26:03,872
And it's at that point that you're doing pure vipassana.

266
00:26:05,295 --> 00:26:07,538
And you won't know it until you come out of it.

267
00:26:07,919 --> 00:26:12,987
When you come out of it, you'll know that you've been in a state where the idea of a self has disappeared.

268
00:26:14,890 --> 00:26:16,231
and with it the sense of time.

269
00:26:18,957 --> 00:26:24,627
It actually comes quite often, believe it or not, but they're in such small little bits that the meditator doesn't actually catch it.

270
00:26:29,978 --> 00:26:38,333
Does that come back to the uncertainty principle, that the nature of what's being observed changes because of the observer?

271
00:26:40,507 --> 00:26:47,878
Well, in a sense, that belongs to the way the observer relates to phenomena out there.

272
00:26:47,919 --> 00:26:49,101
It's more of a scientific thing.

273
00:26:50,963 --> 00:27:01,721
It's more to do with consciousness working at a level of matter where actually what consciousness is doing to matter is actually changing it.

274
00:27:02,561 --> 00:27:12,635
But that's not quite, I don't know whether that works in terms of our internal thing or not, but it's not really what we're trying to do.

275
00:27:12,757 --> 00:27:17,042
What we're trying to do is inform ourselves to find out who we really are, or what we really are.

276
00:27:17,482 --> 00:27:18,464
So we're not this body.

277
00:27:18,904 --> 00:27:22,750
If we were this body, then all we're looking to is annihilation at death.

278
00:27:23,592 --> 00:27:25,555
So you'd end up being an annihilationist.

279
00:27:26,195 --> 00:27:27,657
That's definitely not the Buddhist position.

280
00:27:29,461 --> 00:27:36,147
On the other hand, if you say, well, I am something, so I am this observer, then you fall into the error of eternalism.

281
00:27:36,567 --> 00:27:37,788
And he said he wasn't that either.

282
00:27:39,730 --> 00:27:40,571
So you're really stuck.

283
00:27:41,792 --> 00:27:48,338
So there's something beyond the concepts of something completely ending and something constantly existing.

284
00:27:52,784 --> 00:27:55,547
But the meditation has a practical result.

285
00:27:55,567 --> 00:27:57,087
Because it makes...

286
00:28:00,612 --> 00:28:19,296
Yeah, if you take, for instance, these two positions, the position of the person who's seeking happiness and the position of one who has moved into, for want of a better word, this level of consciousness, or the vipassana state, shall we say.

287
00:28:22,414 --> 00:28:28,723
If you watch a film and your intention is to enjoy the film, I'm going to enjoy this film.

288
00:28:29,865 --> 00:28:32,729
You're saying that to yourself, I'm going, oh great, I'm going to enjoy this film.

289
00:28:33,329 --> 00:28:43,763
You turn the TV on and because you're interested in the film and because you want to enjoy it, you'll enter into the absorption of that film, won't you?

290
00:28:43,785 --> 00:28:49,231
You'll lose a sense of time, lose a sense of self, and you'll wake up at the end of the film and think that was a fantastic film.

291
00:28:49,938 --> 00:28:55,943
Now the problem with that absorption is that it's conditioned us to seek happiness in films.

292
00:28:57,566 --> 00:28:59,647
That's the problem.

293
00:28:59,667 --> 00:29:02,931
Which means that we're always looking for a good film to see so that I can be happy.

294
00:29:07,516 --> 00:29:19,167
How can we watch a film where we appreciate it and yet we don't get that hangover of wanting, needing, a compulsive desire to see films?

295
00:29:21,055 --> 00:29:23,538
So that's what we're learning.

296
00:29:23,577 --> 00:29:34,250
We're learning how to be with something in a completely absorbed way, but not coming off the platform of seeking happiness there.

297
00:29:37,494 --> 00:29:45,644
We're trying to come off the platform of simply wanting to know, simply wanting to experience something in order to understand it.

298
00:29:50,012 --> 00:29:51,977
So it's the same thing in meditation.

299
00:29:52,458 --> 00:29:55,103
The driving force in meditation is interest.

300
00:29:55,624 --> 00:29:56,747
It's a wanting to know.

301
00:29:56,767 --> 00:30:06,807
But is that not in itself a desire to have something?

302
00:30:07,781 --> 00:30:15,595
Well, you've got to be careful here.

303
00:30:15,715 --> 00:30:19,982
It's a striving in order to know what is in the present moment.

304
00:30:20,544 --> 00:30:23,608
What is in the present moment.

305
00:30:23,628 --> 00:30:31,142
So therefore there's no conceptualization, there's no launching into the future, and there's no grabbing into the past for some answer.

306
00:30:31,423 --> 00:30:32,845
It's right here and now.

307
00:30:34,276 --> 00:30:36,397
Therefore it can't be conceptual.

308
00:30:37,138 --> 00:30:38,701
Thought is always an afterthought.

309
00:30:39,421 --> 00:30:40,563
It's always a launching.

310
00:30:44,767 --> 00:30:48,651
If you're in the present moment, there can't be a self, there can't be an ego.

311
00:30:48,671 --> 00:30:49,571
Ego needs time.

312
00:30:51,493 --> 00:30:53,957
It needs time to reflect and needs to know what it wants.

313
00:30:54,017 --> 00:30:57,921
And then it needs to be able to manipulate in order to get what it wants.

314
00:30:59,115 --> 00:31:02,240
Whereas what we're trying to do is to see things as they are now.

315
00:31:02,319 --> 00:31:05,423
That's the interest, to see things as they really are now.

316
00:31:05,463 --> 00:31:08,948
As a scientist might want to do that at the material level.

317
00:31:10,108 --> 00:31:13,574
He wants to see what is happening actually now.

318
00:31:14,454 --> 00:31:22,845
So there's no room to manipulate that now to fit in with what I want because it's happening.

319
00:31:23,885 --> 00:31:25,208
I can't think about it.

320
00:31:28,849 --> 00:31:31,261
Yeah?

321
00:31:31,624 --> 00:31:34,155
Are you saying that there's no such thing as time?

322
00:31:34,900 --> 00:31:35,865
Yeah, absolutely.

323
00:31:36,287 --> 00:31:37,492
It's a concept, yeah.

324
00:31:40,644 --> 00:31:46,276
I presume also, in that state, we don't make any judgments either.

325
00:31:46,296 --> 00:31:46,757
That's right.

326
00:31:47,778 --> 00:31:50,845
You're not saying then, this is good or this is bad.

327
00:31:50,865 --> 00:31:51,726
That's right.

328
00:31:52,468 --> 00:31:55,492
We're talking about meditation now.

329
00:31:56,013 --> 00:32:03,648
If the statement comes up, this is good, this is bad, then that is also observed as a sentence.

330
00:32:03,628 --> 00:32:06,032
There's no need to agree with it or disagree with it.

331
00:32:06,534 --> 00:32:16,128
Because what you're interested in is the mind as it expounds itself into your consciousness.

332
00:32:16,990 --> 00:32:18,311
You're investigating something.

333
00:32:18,732 --> 00:32:23,380
To start judging it would be already to manipulate it, to decide what you don't want to see and what you do want to see.

334
00:32:24,742 --> 00:32:28,648
So one very good example is of a bird watcher.

335
00:32:28,848 --> 00:32:31,272
See, a bird watcher doesn't manipulate the birds.

336
00:32:32,266 --> 00:32:33,288
Just watch the bird.

337
00:32:33,627 --> 00:32:36,192
You watch the bird and at the end you write a book and make a million pounds.

338
00:32:37,773 --> 00:32:38,355
You just watch.

339
00:32:39,457 --> 00:32:40,458
Write your little notes.

340
00:32:40,478 --> 00:32:41,259
That's all you're doing.

341
00:32:41,278 --> 00:32:44,284
You're just trying to find a position in yourself where you're watching.

342
00:32:44,763 --> 00:32:48,128
Then you come to understand, ah, this is causing me suffering.

343
00:32:48,931 --> 00:32:52,516
This is causing me happiness.

344
00:32:52,536 --> 00:32:54,097
This is where real happiness lies.

345
00:32:54,499 --> 00:32:56,961
This is where suffering lies.

346
00:32:56,981 --> 00:33:01,429
If you get it right within us, then of course outwardly we get it right without any problem.

347
00:33:05,864 --> 00:33:08,648
So you take, for instance, a very simple thing once you go out into the world.

348
00:33:08,689 --> 00:33:09,490
Say compassion.

349
00:33:09,851 --> 00:33:10,772
That's a very simple one.

350
00:33:11,314 --> 00:33:12,175
So you want to help people.

351
00:33:13,157 --> 00:33:14,941
It might be just helping somebody across the road.

352
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:16,924
It might be doing something for a charity.

353
00:33:16,944 --> 00:33:17,766
You want to help somebody.

354
00:33:18,768 --> 00:33:21,053
So the ego says this is a very good thing to do.

355
00:33:22,695 --> 00:33:23,778
So you start helping.

356
00:33:23,917 --> 00:33:26,623
Now there's a part of it which is coming out of a wisdom base.

357
00:33:27,682 --> 00:33:31,066
coming out of a desire to alleviate somebody's suffering.

358
00:33:31,527 --> 00:33:34,990
Because we've suffered, we see their suffering, so we want to help them.

359
00:33:35,891 --> 00:33:38,594
Normally speaking, you tend to help people who've suffered like you.

360
00:33:38,614 --> 00:33:44,078
If you've had a drink problem, you tend to be very good at helping people with a drink problem.

361
00:33:44,880 --> 00:33:46,942
It's very simple, there's a relationship to it.

362
00:33:47,423 --> 00:33:51,547
So, you then go to help this person, and of course, you feel good.

363
00:33:53,749 --> 00:33:56,711
And the ego says, when you do that, you feel good.

364
00:33:58,176 --> 00:34:02,877
So then you start doing that, not particularly to want to help the person, but because you want to feel good.

365
00:34:04,747 --> 00:34:05,892
Then you become a do-gooder.

366
00:34:07,744 --> 00:34:08,186
See?

367
00:34:08,646 --> 00:34:13,692
So a do-gooder is somebody who does you the good they want to do to you.

368
00:34:14,773 --> 00:34:16,554
If you ask them to do something else, they get very upset.

369
00:34:19,858 --> 00:34:19,978
See?

370
00:34:20,338 --> 00:34:28,429
So then that's ego coming in, you see, whereas somebody who is helping for the sake of the other, the self can't be there.

371
00:34:28,648 --> 00:34:30,231
They're at the service of the other.

372
00:34:30,550 --> 00:34:32,552
So if the other says, can you do this for me?

373
00:34:33,434 --> 00:34:36,637
Yes, I can, as long as it's skillful, model, and all that sort of stuff.

374
00:34:39,976 --> 00:34:45,224
So the feeling of goodness, the feeling of happiness would still arise, but it doesn't become your aim.

375
00:34:45,684 --> 00:34:47,586
If it becomes your aim, that's self-driven.

376
00:34:50,251 --> 00:34:51,353
It's the same with food, isn't it?

377
00:34:51,994 --> 00:34:52,894
Why do you eat food?

378
00:34:57,061 --> 00:34:59,023
Are you eating there so that you can have a good time?

379
00:35:00,206 --> 00:35:03,090
So that finally you can experience half an hour of delight?

380
00:35:04,172 --> 00:35:06,355
Or are you eating in order to nourish the body?

381
00:35:08,208 --> 00:35:13,795
If you eat in order to nourish the body, you still get the delight, but you don't get the hangover, you don't get the fat.

382
00:35:15,358 --> 00:35:19,423
Because the body will tell you enough, and then you stop, because you don't need to eat more than that.

383
00:35:20,824 --> 00:35:23,628
But if you're finding happiness in food, you can't stop.

384
00:35:26,233 --> 00:35:32,420
You're always stocking up the fridge, there's always a snack, there's always a biscuit.

385
00:35:32,440 --> 00:35:32,601
Why?

386
00:35:32,742 --> 00:35:34,523
Because the self has found happiness there.

387
00:35:35,425 --> 00:35:37,168
It's just killing the body, that's all.

388
00:35:41,248 --> 00:35:50,766
So that distinction between coming from the base of wisdom and coming from the base of self begins here within us as we observe what the self is doing.

389
00:35:51,407 --> 00:35:54,052
And the self is always caught up in that duality.

390
00:35:54,773 --> 00:36:01,586
Wanting, grasping what it likes, pushing away, running away from what it doesn't like.

391
00:36:02,478 --> 00:36:04,480
That's the game at the bottom of the triangle.

392
00:36:06,161 --> 00:36:07,242
Wanting, not wanting.

393
00:36:07,362 --> 00:36:08,362
Wanting, not wanting.

394
00:36:08,603 --> 00:36:13,688
And what you've done is lifted yourself to the apex of that triangle and you're looking down on that game.

395
00:36:16,490 --> 00:36:18,213
You're trying to liberate yourself from that.

396
00:36:19,974 --> 00:36:25,880
Well, you mean to keep living.

397
00:36:28,362 --> 00:36:29,362
Well, that's ego, isn't it?

398
00:36:30,980 --> 00:36:32,603
That would be ego.

399
00:36:32,623 --> 00:36:35,527
That's the self, which says to itself, I am alive.

400
00:36:35,547 --> 00:36:38,954
And then when it defines being alive, it usually defines it as being a human being.

401
00:36:39,554 --> 00:36:42,219
So coming to the end of human life is horrific.

402
00:36:47,889 --> 00:36:50,876
But if there's no self there, there's nothing to die.

403
00:36:52,719 --> 00:36:55,063
But there is nothing to live as others.

404
00:36:56,782 --> 00:36:58,585
You still want to live.

405
00:36:58,606 --> 00:37:00,411
After all I said.

406
00:37:00,670 --> 00:37:02,516
There's no drive towards surviving.

407
00:37:03,918 --> 00:37:11,818
Well, it just sounds a bit, put it this way, there is life.

408
00:37:12,139 --> 00:37:15,246
So long as there is life, one is alive.

409
00:37:15,800 --> 00:37:17,862
I mean, when the Buddha came enlightened, he didn't kill himself.

410
00:37:18,965 --> 00:37:20,126
He didn't say, well, that's it, that's finished.

411
00:37:20,686 --> 00:37:21,489
And jump off a cliff.

412
00:37:23,291 --> 00:37:23,972
He kept living.

413
00:37:24,353 --> 00:37:28,659
He kept living until the end of his, until the natural term of his life came to an end.

414
00:37:30,461 --> 00:37:30,641
Why?

415
00:37:31,583 --> 00:37:32,324
Yeah, it's a good question.

416
00:37:32,364 --> 00:37:32,585
Why?

417
00:37:32,605 --> 00:37:36,110
I mean, you could ask it, you could turn the question around itself.

418
00:37:36,150 --> 00:37:37,693
Why should he kill himself?

419
00:37:38,193 --> 00:37:39,295
He was happy.

420
00:37:39,795 --> 00:37:41,518
He was happy with the way it is.

421
00:37:43,121 --> 00:37:45,063
This is the way it is.

422
00:37:45,753 --> 00:37:48,396
I'm neither happy nor unhappy, this is just the way it is.

423
00:37:53,942 --> 00:38:00,268
But I must say there was also something else, because remember that upon the enlightenment, what was the first thought that came to his mind?

424
00:38:00,367 --> 00:38:05,813
Once he'd actually understood what he'd actually come to experience, what was his first thought?

425
00:38:06,313 --> 00:38:08,456
His first thought was, who can I help?

426
00:38:09,637 --> 00:38:12,621
So with wisdom, compassion arises naturally.

427
00:38:13,697 --> 00:38:20,326
And that set him off on his teaching career.

428
00:38:20,346 --> 00:38:25,693
He didn't just sit there and say, great, I've got it, to hell with everybody else, I'll just keep asking for rice pudding.

429
00:38:29,356 --> 00:38:38,068
You just touched on something that the purpose of enlightenment, I've often heard, it is to help others.

430
00:38:44,815 --> 00:38:46,659
That's the sort of Mahayana thing.

431
00:38:46,858 --> 00:38:48,963
You've been going to the Tibetans, I can see.

432
00:38:48,983 --> 00:38:53,393
Yes, sir.

433
00:38:53,413 --> 00:38:56,079
Because I never agreed with them.

434
00:38:56,099 --> 00:38:57,822
Well, historically it happened the other way.

435
00:38:58,103 --> 00:38:59,786
Historically, the Buddha...

436
00:39:00,525 --> 00:39:05,974
suffered, like us all, and he decided to see whether there was an end of suffering for himself.

437
00:39:06,775 --> 00:39:09,559
Having done that, then this thought came, who can I help?

438
00:39:10,239 --> 00:39:14,806
So it would be silly, from his point of view, to say that he had started off in order to help others.

439
00:39:14,847 --> 00:39:16,208
He started off wanting to help himself.

440
00:39:16,989 --> 00:39:22,898
Having done that, he then goes out and can help others.

441
00:39:22,958 --> 00:39:25,621
Mahayana tended to be a reaction against

442
00:39:25,601 --> 00:39:53,954
the early Buddhism which was very much about individuals becoming enlightened so they tend to but you can see that compassion is wisdom in action it just flows and then the Buddha put it in the Eightfold Path as soon as you have right understanding your attitude changes once your attitude changes your speech, your action, your livelihood changes just a natural outflow

